                        <p>To show how to execute POST requests, we used the following snipping of PowerShell snipping of code: </p>
                        <p><code>$postData = @{nombre='TestFromPowerShell';apellido='TestFromPowershell';telefono='TestFromPowershell'}</code><br>
                            then <br>
                           <code>Invoke-WebRequest -Method POST -Uri http://localhost:4001/api/contact -Body $postData -UseBasicParsing</code></p>

                    <p>To be able to execute those snipping of code successfully, you have to be running the project locally on the port 4001. 
                        The object <code>$postData</code> stores an example of the JSON data that was summited through the <code>/api/contact/</code> direction. 
                        <code> Invoke-WebRequest</code> sends HTTP and HTTPS requests to a web page or web service. It parses the response and returns collections of links, images, and other significant HTML
                          elements.<br> 
                          The <code>Invoke-WebRequest</code> method is prepared with -Body defines the body JSON object. </p>
                      

